NAME: Deptford
ACCESS_DSC: Access from Bairnsdale is along Deptford Rd but is 4WD only (deep river crossing). Access for 2WD is via Bruthen - turn onto Great Alpine Rd, then Engineers Rd and Deptford Rd.
COMMENTS: Once a small mining village situated on the Nicholson River, Deptford provides opportunities for both day visitors and campers with good access to the Nicholson River, plenty of spots for a picnic and nearby walks.
LABEL: Deptford
CLOS_DESC: Closed due to fire activity in the area
CAMPING_C: Dispersed camping with good access to the Nicholson River. The main camping area is located on the east side of the Nicholson River (deep river crossing).
HERITAGE_C: Old gold mining relics.
PADDLING_C: River good for paddling.
PICNIC_C: Plenty of picnic spots with good access to the Nicholson River.

NAME: Bark Sheds
ACCESS_DSC: Access is from the Great Alpine Rd, approx. 20 mins drive from Bruthen.
COMMENTS: A scenic picnic area located next to the Tambo River. The site has a shelter and a toilet as well as informal camping sites.
LABEL: Bark Sheds
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.

NAME: Bentley Plain
ACCESS_DSC: Access to the plains is via the township of Ensay and Bentley Plain Rd from the south and via Nunniong Rd and Bentley Plain Rd from the north.
COMMENTS: Bentley Plain is a formal camp site situated within the Bentley Plain Natural Features and Scenic Reserve. The site contains a historic forestry hut (refuge only, no fireplace), fire pit, toilets, picnic shelter and a bbq. There is a grassy area within t
LABEL: Bentley Plain
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.

NAME: Costicks Weir
ACCESS_DSC: Access is via the Old Colquhoun Rd off the Princes Hwy, west of Nowa Nowa township.
COMMENTS: This is an historic fire dam built in the 1940s by the local Women's Army. It was built to provide a reliable water supply after the disastrous 1939 bushfires. The site is adjacent to the East Gippsland Rail Trail and provides a quiet spot for a picnic o
LABEL: Costicks Weir
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
HERITAGE_C: Historic fire dam built in 1940s.

NAME: Tomahawk Hut
ACCESS_DSC: From Mansfield follow the Mt. Buller Rd to Sawmill Settlement, turn left on Carters Rd, follow for 11kms. Turn left onto Buckland Spur Tk.
COMMENTS: Tomahawk Hut was originally built in 1927 by Forest Officer Arthur Dale. Rebuilt in 2007, the hut is an example of an early Forest Commission Hut in the Alpine area of Victoria. The Hut has an open fire and the site also has a picnic table and fireplace.
LABEL: Tomahawk Hut
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: This site is magnificent and rich in history,Originally being built as a base for road building crews. You are able to utilise to Hut for your camping needs and the road is 2WD accessible what more could you want.
PICNIC_C: A perfect place to stop and have a picnic on your journey through the Mansfield State Forest, taking in the history of the area and enjoying the time you spend exploring.

NAME: Ruoaks
ACCESS_DSC: Off North Creek Road at Merton, turn right down Ruoaks Road, 2wd on dirt road not suitable for caravans.
COMMENTS: Basic Campsite for three sites
LABEL: Ruoaks
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.

NAME: Snakes Reserve
ACCESS_DSC: From Jamieson follow the Jamieson-Woods Point Rd towards Woods Point. Turn left into camp area at Snakes Reserve Camping sign.
COMMENTS: This spot is very popular and you can see why, you're surrounded by tall Eucalypt native forest, large shady trees and ample space to camp on lush grass. Stopping next to the Goulburn River is a perfect place to stop, with plenty of activities to underta
LABEL: Snakes Reserve
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: This spot offers a large expanse of grassy and shady spots, being suitable for both small and larger groups.
CAMPERVANC: A very large grassed area offers the perfect spot to set up your caravan or camper trailer for the weekend.
FISHING_C: The Goulburn River is excellent for fishing, with the main species caught being the Rainbow and Brown Trout and Perch Species.
PADDLING_C: With excellent access to the nearby Goulburn River this spot is great to launch your kayak or canoe and go out on the water exploring for the day.

NAME: Blue Hole Reserve
ACCESS_DSC: From Jamieson follow the Jamieson-Woods Point Rd towards Woods Point until left turn into camp area at Blue Hole Reserve Camping sign.
COMMENTS: Set on the banks of the Goulburn River this grassy campground is popular with fisherman and campers alike. The large pools in the river adjacent to the campground provide good swimming holes to beat the summer heat or just to relax and unwind.
LABEL: Blue Hole Reserve
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: Good camping along the Goulburn River.

NAME: Tunnel Bend
ACCESS_DSC: From Jamieson follow the Jamieson-Woods Point Rd towards Woods Point until left turn into camp area at Tunnel Bend Reserve sign.
COMMENTS: Tunnel Bend is named after the 100m tunnel built in 1884 linking the 4 km long hand cut water race to Howqua. The tunnel entrance can be viewed near the base of the tunnel steps at tunnel bend, the water race was constructed to carry water to power the H
LABEL: Tunnel Bend
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: Camping along the upper stretches of the Goulburn river is perfect all year round. This site offers a large expanse of large, open grassy areas perfect for medium and large groups of campers.
CAMPERVANC: This large flat area allows for easy caravan manoeuvring and setting up.
FISHING_C: There are several modes of fishing you can undertake during your stay at Tunnel bend, why not try your hand at fly fishing, fish from the bank or put your canoe in and fish from there. The upper reaches of the Goulburn river are perfect for trout fishing
PADDLING_C: Throughout the Spring and early Summer season this area is perfect for kayakers and canoers with ample water in the river system you could take a leisurely float downstream.

NAME: Flour Bag Reserve
ACCESS_DSC: From Jamieson follow the Jamieson-Woods Point Rd towards Woods Point until Left turn into camp area at Flour Bag Camping area sign.
LABEL: Flour Bag Reserve
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: Flour Bag Reserve is located at the junction of Flourbag Creek and the Goulburn River. The site is a popular base for exploring the nearby gold mining history and the outdoors. This best for smaller groups that enjoy having the entire site to themselves.

NAME: Link Road
LABEL: Link Road
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.

NAME: Toorongo Falls Site One
ACCESS_DSC: Head east from Noojee on the Mount Baw Baw Tourist Road for approximately 2km and take a left turn into Toorongo Valley Road.  The site is accessed on the right after about 10km along this well-formed gravel road.
COMMENTS: An expansive drive-in hilly camping spot with easy access to the Toorongo River. Tall trees are dotted around on site with a background of bushy hills. Picnicking and open BBQ opportunities feature.
LABEL: Toorongo Falls Site One
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: Open or shaded campsites are offered on this hilly site, with easy access to a pretty section of the Toorongo River.  The Toorongo River becomes part of the Latrobe River near Noojee, flowing through the Latrobe Valley and into the Gippsland Lakes.
CAMPERVANC: A hilly, expansive site that can host small caravans and camper trailers.  There are plenty of open fire pits to light a fire and a short walk up hill takes you to basic toilet facilities. Can get muddy in winter.
PICNIC_C: Easy river access, makes this site a good spot to have a picnic.  You may choose to picnic here before moving on to  the Toorongo Falls and Amphitheatre walks.  There are several informal open fire pits to use to warm up your stay.

NAME: Anderson Mill
ACCESS_DSC: From Marysville take Lyell street to the south which runs into Paradise Plains road.  Head past the Marysville reservoir before reaching Anderson Mill road.  Here turn right and continue on for approximately 4km.  The Anderson Mill campground is on your
COMMENTS: Nestled in the Great Dividing Range this isolated peaceful site, Anderson Mill is available for camping, picnicking and provides horse yard facilities for riders enjoying the Bicentennial National Trail in a bushland setting a short drive into Marysville
LABEL: Anderson Mill
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: This quiet campsite is set off the road with grassy sites, toilet and picnic table facilities.  Set back from the road under the gum tree canopy, this site is a focal point for multi purpose recreational pursuits.
CAMPERVANC: Anderson Mill has larger areas that can accommodate camper trailers and small caravans.
HERITAGE_C: The historic Anderson No. 1 Mill site was one of the most productive sawmills in the region, supporting a small community, shops and even a school.  Living in the forest the early timber workers cut the huge Mountain Ash trees with a cross cut saw and ba
HORSERIDEC: Anderson Mill site is perfect for those that love a day forest trail ride or intend to extend their stay and camp with their horses.  The loop camp road is ideal for floats and the horse yards can accommodate larger trail riding groups with a nearby wate

NAME: Stockmans Reward
ACCESS_DSC: From Marysville - Take the Woods Point road.  After 18km veer left at the Cumberland Junction then turn left down Eildon Warburton road.  From Warburton - Follow the Warburton Woods Point Road and turn right at Cumberland Junction then left down Eildon W
COMMENTS: A popular camping site located in the middle of the Upper Big River State forest.  This site can accommodate family and friends groups and provides a base to experience the adventures that Big River offers.  Sit back and enjoy a break from the every day
LABEL: Stockmans Reward
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: Sitting at the junction of the Torbreck and Big River, Stockmans Reward is a large flat campsite utilised in the 1920's for deep lead mining using a large steam-driven dredge.  Now the area can accommodate large groups with caravans, camper trailers and
CAMPERVANC: Larger sites here to accommodate small caravans and camper trailers.
FISHING_C: Try your luck fishing the Torbreck and Big River there are small pools of slow moving water where native trout can be found.

NAME: Number One Camp
ACCESS_DSC: From Melbourne, take the Hume Highway to the Broadford exit; turn right here along Spur road to Main Mountain road.  Continue down Main Mountain road for approximately 2 km to Two Tees road, turn left and drive on to the five ways.  No 1. Camp is on the
COMMENTS: Situated in the heart of Mt Disappointment State Forest this campsite/picnic area is popular with visitors that like to engage in trailbiking, four wheel driving or just relaxing in the bush setting away from Melbourne.  Here there are sites to accommoda
LABEL: Number One Camp
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: In the 1940's the site housed seventy-five Italian P.O.W's supervised by members of the Australian military.  The P.O.W's cut firewood, cleared timber and built forest roads.  Post World War 2, European immigrant workers, encouraged to settle in Australi
PICNIC_C: At the entrance to No. 1 Camp there are grassy areas equipped with a picnic shelter, table, toilet facilities, wood fire pit and ample parking for family and friends.  Take a break from your activities to sit back, relax and enjoy the bush setting.

NAME: Mugwamp Hut
ACCESS_DSC: From Beaufort, turn north towards Raglan and after 11km, turn left down Raglan-Mt Cole Road. After 3km continue onto Mount Cole Road and after 11.7 km, turn left onto Dawson Rock Road.
COMMENTS: This site provides basic facilities for picnicking or camping and links in with the overnight Beeripmo walking track. Due to its small size, the site is suitable for small groups only.
LABEL: Mugwamp Hut
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: Mugwamp is a small open camping area with some large shady eucalypts, adjacent to Mugwamp Hut. The small grassed area includes a picnic table, drop toilet and wood-fired BBQ and is suitable for tent based camping with opportunities for walks along the ad
HERITAGE_C: Mugwamp Hut is believed to have been built in the 1890s as shelter for timber workers in a nearby mill. There were once many such huts in the Mt Cole area but all others have been demolished or lost. The Mugwamp Hut is the last remaining hut in the Mt Co
PICNIC_C: This small open picnic area next to Mugwamp Hut is a pleasant spot for a picnic with basic facilities and opportunities to walk on the nearby Beerimpo walking track and out to Mount Buangor.

NAME: Collins Flat
ACCESS_DSC: From Dargo travel 6km (10 minutes) up the Dargo High Plains Road and turn right onto Upper Dargo Road. Collins Flat is located at the 15km mark.
COMMENTS: Collins Flat is the last of the main camping areas along the Upper Dargo Road but is just as scenic as the previous sites.
LABEL: Collins Flat
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.

NAME: Craigs Hut
ACCESS_DSC: From Mansfield follow the Mt. Buller Rd to Mirimbah. Turn left onto Mt. Stirling Rd and follow to Telephone Box Junction (T.B.J). From here, The Circuit Rd can be driven in either direction and is accessible to all vehicles, but can have rough sections.
COMMENTS: Craigs Hut was originally constructed as a film set for the 1983 Australian movie ''The Man from Snowy River.'' The hut was fully rebuilt in 1993 but subsequently destroyed by the 2006 Great Divide wildfire. The hut was again rebuilt in 2008. Located on
LABEL: Craigs Hut
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: The camping area is located on Clear Hills Tk 200m to the South-East of the Craigs Hut carpark. It is suitable for tents and offroad campervans.
PICNIC_C: A perfect spot to stop and have a rest on your tour along Ciruit Road, the historical Craigs hut with views over the alpine valley around you makes for a stunning backdrop.

NAME: Long Point
ACCESS_DSC: Turn off the Buchan Rd onto Long Point Track following the track for 7km. Access is limited to a steep single lane track, four wheel drive access only for the last 200m.
COMMENTS: Set on a sandy section of the Mighty Snowy River enjoy your stay getting back to nature.
LABEL: Long Point
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: Camp sites are usually open but due to flooding events campground is ever evolving.
PADDLING_C: Great site to start paddling from and or finishing point from higher up the Snowy.

NAME: Woods Point
ACCESS_DSC: Via 'B' Rd Orbost, following Garnetts Track along until the turnoff to Woods Point Track. A short drive from the township of Orbost, following the river along the fertile Snowy River Flats.
COMMENTS: Set on the sandy banks of the Snowy River in amongst warm temperate rainforest you will find a well maintained selection of camping and day picnicking areas, wildlife watching and river based activities.
LABEL: Woods Point
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: Well maintained camping area.
HORSERIDEC: Facilities are provided for horses- secure yards at camp ground
PADDLING_C: Excellent area to finish a paddle from up stream with easy river access, or to start a paddle down stream to Orbost or Marlo.
PICNIC_C: Several picnic tables, and BBQ facilities at site.

NAME: Goongerah
ACCESS_DSC: Via the Bonang Highway Goongerah, campground is sign posted onto the Ellery Creek Track.
COMMENTS: Set on the banks of the picturesque Brodribb River, enjoy this tranquil camp set amongst the manna gums, base yourself for a night or a week and enjoy the tall forests that East Gippsland has to offer.
LABEL: Goongerah
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: Several camping areas on both sides of the river, camping areas seperated by the headwater of the Brodribb River.
PICNIC_C: Ample spots to set up a picnic lunch whilst enjoying the serenity.

NAME: Choof Choof
ACCESS_DSC: Situated south of Cann River, follow the bitumen down the Tamboon Road and then follow the signs to the right towards Furnell Landing, veer right into Choof Choof Track and proceed to the campground.
COMMENTS: Situated on the banks of the Cann River this small campsite provides facilities for kayak launching for quick access to the premier fishing grounds of Lake Furnell and Tamboon Inlet
LABEL: Choof Choof
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: Basic camp site and facilities designed for a small group of campers
FISHING_C: Once a local secret, cast a line from the bank of the camp or walk along the choof choof walk and find a nice rock to sit back and enjoy the scenery
PADDLING_C: Canoe launching facilities provided at the campground with a day use carpark available for use

NAME: Ada River
ACCESS_DSC: Access is via Errinundra Road, approximately 12 kilometres to the North from the Combienbar/Club Terrace Rd. Access closed to the North at present.
COMMENTS: The gateway to the Errinundra Plateau, this site is set amongst our tall East Gippsland forest on the banks of the picturesque Ada River.
LABEL: Ada River
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: An abundance of grassy, shaded camping areas located on the surrounding river flats
FISHING_C: Trout streams closeby including the Ada, Bemm, Combienbar, and Errinundra Rivers.
PICNIC_C: Great picnic facilities, including BBQs, Toilet and Tables

NAME: Moscow Villa
ACCESS_DSC: Access to Moscow Villa from Swifts Creek is via Nunniong Road and Bentleys Plain Road, from Ensay is via Bentleys Plain Road.
COMMENTS: Built in the 1940's by a local Swifts Creek residence and used as a summer residence for him when on Fire Tower Lookout duties. Complete with stone fireplace, wooden floors and tin roof. Outside the hut is room for camping, with picnic tables and a toile
LABEL: Moscow Villa
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
HERITAGE_C: Hut

NAME: Dog'S Grave
ACCESS_DSC: Access is via the Birregun Road. from Swifts Creek, head out along the road to Cassilis, then onto the Upper Livingstone Road and Birregun Rd.
COMMENTS: A quiet camping area off the Birregun Road, with a small hut (with pot belly stove), picnic table, fire pit, toilet and room for camping. The site has a historic Dog's Grave.
LABEL: Dog'S Grave
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
HERITAGE_C: Gravesite of dog.

NAME: Wilsons Hut
ACCESS_DSC: From Bendoc, travel south down Clarkeville Road before turning left onto Marriot Track where you will proceed a short distance (~1.2km) before arriving at the hut.
COMMENTS: This well restored high country hut is a great place to base yourself for the night while you explore the vast array of history that the Bendoc region has to offer.
LABEL: Wilsons Hut
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: Site development currently underway to accommodate for overnight camping outside of the historical hut
HERITAGE_C: Built more than a century ago, this restored hut is a rare example of a slab hut constructed using vertical timber slabs of locally sourced forest timber species  bush carpentry at its best!
PICNIC_C: Picnic facilities including tables and fireplaces available to support day visitors and overnight campers

NAME: Paddy Lees Crossing
ACCESS_DSC: From Boisdale take the Boisdale-Valencia Creek Road To Valencia Creek. Turn right onto Valencia Creek Briagolong Road and then left onto Moroka Rd. Follow for 30 minutes or 17km until you reach the crossing.
COMMENTS: This picnic area is located on Valencia Creek.
LABEL: Paddy Lees Crossing
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.

NAME: Valencia Creek Picnic Area
ACCESS_DSC: From Boisdale take the Boisdale-Valencia Creek Road To Valencia Creek. Turn right onto Valencia Creek Briagolong Road and then left onto Moroka Rd. Follow for approximately 9km or 15 minutes, the campsite access track is located on the left.
LABEL: Valencia Creek Picnic Area
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: A medium sized camping area with space for multiple family groups.
PICNIC_C: A good spot to explore Valencia Creek just off Moroka Road.

NAME: Wombat Crossing Camp Site B
ACCESS_DSC: From the township of Boisdale travel North on Boisdale-Valencia Creek Road to Wombat Rd. Turn left off Wombat Rd onto OKeefe Rd The access track is off to the left after approximately 2km. Follow this track for a couple of hundred metres to Wombat campsi
COMMENTS: The middle and largest Wombat campsite. Walking access only to the river.
LABEL: Wombat Crossing Camp Site B
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.

NAME: Wombat Crossing Camp Site C
ACCESS_DSC: From the township of Boisdale travel North on Boisdale-Valencia Creek Road to Wombat Rd. Turn left off Wombat Rd onto OKeefe Rd. Continue straight after the first two campsites to reach Wombat campsite C.
COMMENTS: Small campsite at the end of O'Keefes Rd. Campsite is located in the forest with walking access only to the river.
LABEL: Wombat Crossing Camp Site C
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.

NAME: Wombat Crossing Camp Site A
ACCESS_DSC: From the township of Boisdale travel North on Boisdale-Valencia Creek Road to Wombat Rd. Turn left off Wombat Rd onto OKeefe Rd and follow for approximately 1.3km to the Wombat campsite A on the left.
LABEL: Wombat Crossing Camp Site A
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.

NAME: Blue Gum Flat
ACCESS_DSC: From Mansfield head towards Mount Buller, turning right on Mansfield Woods Point road follow this for 9.5 km before turning right onto Piries-Goughs Bay Rd, following this road for 7.3km before turning right onto Walshs Rd. Follow Walshs Road for 7.4 Km
COMMENTS:
Situated on the banks of Lake Eildon, this site is a popular destination for boats, fishermen, campers and trail bike riders alike. Behind you, you will see an expansive area of native bushland worth exploring.
This site can become busy in the warmer mo
LABEL: Blue Gum Flat
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: This large campground is great for large groups and several smaller groups. With larger canopy Eucalypts offering much needed shade in the warmer months.
CAMPERVANC: This site can be accessed by small caravans and camper trailers, although be aware that you may have to travel long distances on dirt roads.
FISHING_C:
This area is perfect for offshore fishing with the lake coming to a narrower section. This area is also perfect for trolling during April - July and September  November.

This area was formally known as the pines before being rehabilitated and revegetated back to native forests. Raised up overlooking Lake Eildon you will have picturesque views over the lake.

LABEL: Picnic Point

CAMPERVANC: This site can be accessed by small caravans and camper trailers, although be aware that you may have to travel long distances on dirt roads.
FISHING_C:
If you have bought a boat with you, you have good chances of going out and completing some deep-water trolling for Murray Cod. Closer to the shore you have the chance to challenge yourself and catch some redfin or trout species.

NAME: Long Gully
ACCESS_DSC: From Mansfield head towards Mount Buller, turning right on Mansfield Woods Point road follow this for 9.5 km before turning right onto Piries-Goughs Bay Rd, following this road for 7.3km before turning right onto Walshs Rd. Follow Walshs Road for 9.5Km a
COMMENTS:
This site is located close to Goughs bay and can therefore be busy during peak season. You can enjoy connecting back to nature at this site with native species surrounding you and offering shade in the warmer months. 
This is a central spot for several
LABEL: Long Gully
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: This area is in one of lake Eildons many small inlets, offering a sheltered campsite with plenty of much needed shade during the warmer months.
CAMPERVANC: This site can be accessed by caravans and camper trailers, although be aware that you may have to travel long distances on dirt roads.
FISHING_C:
This is an excellent spot to conduct offshore trolling during Spring and early Summer. This spot is a good challenge for any good fisherman, try your luck from the shore or from your boat.
Please be aware that if fishing you will need to hold a current
PADDLING_C: Canoeing and kayaking are very popular in Lake Eildon and you can see why once youre out on the water yourself. The vast expanse of the lake and the offshoots and tributaries can easily be explored by paddling around the lake. You will be able to see wat

NAME: Dandos
ACCESS_DSC: Heading south out of Gellibrand, turn left onto Gellibrand East Road (you will see a signpost for Dandos Campground).  Follow this road, which becomes Lardners Track, for approximately 12km then turn left at Sayers Vista.  After 200m turn left at the sig
COMMENTS: Dandos is situated on a tranquil bend of the Gellibrand River on a north facing, spacious flat. The site has day-visitor and camping areas, with picnic tables, fire places with barbeque plates, toilets and a large open grassy area where kids can play.
LABEL: Dandos
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: Dandos has about 20 campsites located under a light canopy of eucalypt trees. The site has toilets, picnic tables and fireplaces with barbeque plates. Water is available from the Gellibrand River, however it is advisable to boil this water before drinkin
CAMPERVANC: Sites are large enough for most campervans/ trailers.
PICNIC_C: Dandos picnic area is in between the camping areas, situated adjacent to the Gellibrand River. There are picnic tables, fireplaces with iron plates for barbequing and toilets.

NAME: North Maintongoon
ACCESS_DSC: From Mansfield head towards Mount Buller, turning right on Mansfield Woods Point road follow this for 9.5 km before turning right onto Piries-Goughs Bay Rd, following this road for 7.3km before turning right onto Walshs Rd. Follow Walshs Road for 29.5Km
COMMENTS: With so many possible activities surrounding you (fishing, motorbike riding, water sports and four-wheel driving) why wouldnt you want to utilise this camp site. From your camp you will have views over Lake Eildon and the Delatite Arm and in the off seas
LABEL: North Maintongoon
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: This campsite, across from Lake Eildon is on a slight slope but is often uncrowded due to the distance from the reserve entrance. Offering wide open spaces and shade from the surrounding revegetated native forest species this is a perfect for large group
CAMPERVANC:
This site is accessible for large and small caravans and camper trailers, although be aware that there is a long period spent on a dirt road to get to the site and some tight corners. 

Please note  the site is on a slightly sloping aspect.

LABEL: Huggetts Crossing

PICNIC_C: A nice spot to stop for lunch by Donnellys Creek on the Aberfeldy 4WD route. This site has a picnic table and wood fired BBQ facilities. Please remember to take all rubbish with you when you leave.

NAME: Rumpffs
ACCESS_DSC: From Licola follow the Licola-Jamieson Rd (C486) for 9km, turn Right onto Link Rd and then Left onto Glencairn Rd. From here continue 18km on Glencairn and Middle Ridge Road. The campsites are located on the right about 1km after Middle Ridge Road crosse
COMMENTS: Rumpff's Flat is located on the Mount Skene Creek just prior to it flowing into the Barkley River. This quiet bush setting is accessed via a scenic drive through the unique Barkley State Forest.
LABEL: Rumpffs
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: Rumpffs camping area is suitable for family groups exploring the scenic forest areas around the Barkley River. Access is limited in wet weather. Please take your rubbish home so the site can be enjoyed by future visitors.
HORSERIDEC: The Bicentennial Trail crosses Mt Skene Creek just downstream from Rumpffs campsite.

NAME: North Camp
ACCESS_DSC: From Mansfield head towards Mount Buller, turning right on Mansfield Woods Point road follow this for 9.5 km before turning right onto Piries-Goughs Bay Rd, following this road for 7.3km before turning right onto Walshs Rd. Follow Walshs Road for 16.5Km
COMMENTS: Located on the shores of Lake Eildon this site has vast views over the Delatite arm. It was originally used as pine plantations before being revegetated to its current state. This area is used for several recreational activities, including: fishing, four
LABEL: North Camp
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: This is a small campsite overlooking lake Eildon and is used by many recreational forest users. It is a site perfect for medium sized groups and is located close to the waters edge when the lake is full.
CAMPERVANC: This site can be accessed by caravans and camper trailers, although be aware that you may have to travel long distances on dirt roads.
FISHING_C:
The perfect spot to throw a line in and see what you can hook. From the shores you will have a good chance at catching native species and redfin and if you have a boat you can take it out on the water and lure or bait cast or deep-water troll.

NAME: Reids Quarry
ACCESS_DSC: From Marysville - Take the Woods Point road.  After 18km veer left at the Cumberland Junction then turn left down Eildon Warburton road.  From Warburton - Follow the Warburton Woods Point Road and turn right at Cumberland Junction then left down Eildon W
COMMENTS: Nestled under the trees, this campsite provides a shady spot for camping with either tents, swags, campervans or even caravans.  From here you can explore the adventures of Big River State forest.
LABEL: Reids Quarry
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: Reid Quarry opens up to a spacious campground to either pitch a tent or camper trailer under some of the large native and European trees remnants of the past users of this area.  This camp has pit toilet facilities and sites that can accommodate larger f
FISHING_C: The Big River provides miles upon miles of productive, picturesque fishing for eager small-to-medium trout in the riffles, and more challenging slow-water fishing for much larger specimens hiding the in the numerous deep pools which populate its course.

NAME: Comet Flat Reserve
ACCESS_DSC: From Woodspoint head South East from the town ship of Woodspoint.
COMMENTS: Comet Flat is stretched out along a riverbank about 4 km south-east of Woods Point. A 4WD is recommended to access the camping area from that township  take the Johnson Hill Track. Swimming and fishing are the main activities here, and theres also bushwa
LABEL: Comet Flat Reserve
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: This is a large camping area beside the Goulburn River, surrounding by tall Eucalypt species and native grasses. There is ample room fro large groups and you'll often see four wheel driving groups utilising this spot.
HERITAGE_C: Spend you time exploring the historical town of Woodspoint and the surrounding historical mining areas.

NAME: Stringybark Camping Area
ACCESS_DSC: This large campsite is located along the Tatong Tolmie Road.
COMMENTS: Stringybark campground offers both shady and sunny camping sites with some facilities including picnic tables and fire pits. There is a large cleared area suitable for playing ball games or flying kites.  Two double toilets service the campground.  A wal
LABEL: Stringybark Camping Area
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.

NAME: Timbarra Central
ACCESS_DSC: Access is directly off the Timbarra Rd, south of Buchan. The access track is 4WD only.
COMMENTS: Camping area located next to the Timbarra River. The site has formal campsites marked, fire places and a toilet. Access is with 4wd vehicles only.
LABEL: Timbarra Central
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPERVANC: 4WD only

NAME: Edi Cutting
ACCESS_DSC: Located 27km south of Oxley on the Wangaratta-Whitfield road, a couple of kilometres past Edi itself. Access is either via Wangaratta from the north or by taking the Snow Road turnoff from the Hume Hwy at Glenrowan from the south.
LABEL: Edi Cutting
CLOS_DESC: Due to risks associated with Coronavirus (COVID-19), this site will be closed to camping until further notice.
CAMPING_C: A very popular area, particularly during holiday periods. Most sites have good shade from large Red Gums and easy access to the King river. All sites have drive through vehicle access. The two distinct areas can be isolated from each other in flood event
CAMPERVANC: A very popular area, particularly during holiday periods. Most sites have good shade from large Red Gums and easy access to the King river. All sites have drive through vehicle access. The two distinct areas can be isolated from each other in flood event
FISHING_C: Easy access to the King river is available across the entire site. Deep pools, shallow riffles and small rapids provide a variety of fishing opportunities.
